{% extends 'shells/docs.html.twig' %}
{% block title %}Multi-node Broker — php-via Docs{% endblock %}
{% block content %}
<article>
    <h1>Multi-node Broker</h1>
    <p>
        By default php-via keeps all state in a single process. That's correct for most deployments —
        OpenSwoole handles thousands of concurrent SSE connections comfortably in one worker.
        When you need to run multiple servers or containers, a <strong>broker</strong> fans out
        <code>broadcast()</code> calls so every node can react to changes that happened on any other node.
    </p>

    <h2 id="when-you-need-it">When do you need a broker?</h2>
    <p>You need a broker when:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>You run more than one php-via process (horizontal scaling, zero-downtime deploys)</li>
        <li>You use <strong>ROUTE</strong>, <strong>SESSION</strong>, or <strong>GLOBAL</strong> scopes and clients can connect to different nodes</li>
        <li>You use <strong>TAB</strong> scope only — you <em>don't</em> need a broker; TAB is fully isolated per connection anyway</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        The <code>InMemoryBroker</code> (the default) is correct for single-node setups. It has zero
        overhead and no external dependencies. Only add a broker when you have a concrete reason to scale out.
    </p>

    <h2 id="inmemorybroker">InMemoryBroker (default)</h2>
    <p>
        No configuration needed. This is the broker used when you don't call <code>withBroker()</code>:
    </p>
    {% code 'php' %}{% verbatim %}
// These are equivalent — InMemoryBroker is the implicit default
$config = new Config();
$config = (new Config())->withBroker(new InMemoryBroker());
{% endverbatim %}{% endcode %}

    <h2 id="redisbroker">RedisBroker</h2>
    <p>
        Uses Redis pub/sub to relay scope invalidations across nodes. Requires the
        <code>ext-redis</code> PHP extension and <code>SWOOLE_HOOK_ALL</code> (enabled automatically
        by php-via). The broker opens two coroutine connections per worker: one for publish, one
        for the subscribe loop.
    </p>

    <h3 id="redis-basic">Basic setup</h3>
    {% code 'php' %}{% verbatim %}
use Mbolli\PhpVia\Broker\RedisBroker;

$config->withBroker(new RedisBroker('127.0.0.1', 6379));
{% endverbatim %}{% endcode %}

    <h3 id="redis-auth">Authentication</h3>
    <p>
        Pass <code>$password</code> for <code>requirepass</code> setups, or both
        <code>$password</code> and <code>$username</code> for Redis 6+ ACL users. Keep credentials
        out of source code — use environment variables or a secrets manager.
    </p>
    {% code 'php' %}{% verbatim %}
// requirepass (Redis default auth)
$config->withBroker(new RedisBroker(
    host: 'redis.internal',
    password: $_ENV['REDIS_PASSWORD'],
));

// ACL user (Redis 6+)
$config->withBroker(new RedisBroker(
    host: 'redis.internal',
    password: $_ENV['REDIS_PASSWORD'],
    username: 'php-via',
));
{% endverbatim %}{% endcode %}
    <p>
        The minimal ACL permissions required are <code>+subscribe +publish +ping &amp;via:broadcast</code>
        (or whichever channel name you configure).
    </p>

    <h3 id="redis-tls">TLS</h3>
    {% code 'php' %}{% verbatim %}
// TLS — verify against system CA bundle
$config->withBroker(new RedisBroker(
    host: 'redis.internal',
    port: 6380,
    password: $_ENV['REDIS_PASSWORD'],
    tls: true,
));

// TLS with a custom CA (self-signed or internal PKI)
$config->withBroker(new RedisBroker(
    host: 'redis.internal',
    port: 6380,
    password: $_ENV['REDIS_PASSWORD'],
    tls: true,
    tlsCaFile: '/etc/ssl/my-ca.pem',
));
{% endverbatim %}{% endcode %}

    <h3 id="redis-channel">Custom channel</h3>
    <p>
        If multiple apps share the same Redis instance, give each app a distinct channel so their
        broadcast traffic doesn't cross-contaminate:
    </p>
    {% code 'php' %}{% verbatim %}
$config->withBroker(new RedisBroker(channel: 'myapp:broadcast'));
{% endverbatim %}{% endcode %}

    <h3 id="redis-constructor">Full constructor signature</h3>
    {% code 'php' %}{% verbatim %}
new RedisBroker(
    string  $host     = '127.0.0.1',
    int     $port     = 6379,
    ?string $password = null,   // #[SensitiveParameter]
    ?string $username = null,
    string  $channel  = 'via:broadcast',
    bool    $tls      = false,
    ?string $tlsCaFile = null,
)
{% endverbatim %}{% endcode %}

    <h2 id="natsbroker">NatsBroker</h2>
    <p>
        Uses a raw OpenSwoole coroutine TCP socket with the minimal NATS protocol — no extra PHP
        extension required beyond OpenSwoole itself. Good choice for containerised deployments where
        NATS already runs for other services.
    </p>
    <h3 id="nats-basic">Basic setup</h3>
    {% code 'php' %}{% verbatim %}
use Mbolli\PhpVia\Broker\NatsBroker;

$config->withBroker(new NatsBroker('127.0.0.1', 4222));
{% endverbatim %}{% endcode %}

    <h3 id="nats-auth">Token authentication</h3>
    {% code 'php' %}{% verbatim %}
$config->withBroker(new NatsBroker(
    host: 'nats.internal',
    authToken: $_ENV['NATS_TOKEN'],
));
{% endverbatim %}{% endcode %}

    <h3 id="nats-tls">TLS</h3>
    {% code 'php' %}{% verbatim %}
// TLS — verify against system CA bundle (port 4243 is the TLS convention)
$config->withBroker(new NatsBroker(host: 'nats.internal', port: 4243, tls: true));

// TLS + custom CA + token
$config->withBroker(new NatsBroker(
    host: 'nats.internal',
    port: 4243,
    authToken: $_ENV['NATS_TOKEN'],
    tls: true,
    tlsCaFile: '/etc/ssl/my-ca.pem',
));
{% endverbatim %}{% endcode %}

    <h3 id="nats-subject">Custom subject</h3>
    {% code 'php' %}{% verbatim %}
$config->withBroker(new NatsBroker(subject: 'myapp.broadcast'));
{% endverbatim %}{% endcode %}

    <h3 id="nats-constructor">Full constructor signature</h3>
    {% code 'php' %}{% verbatim %}
new NatsBroker(
    string  $host      = '127.0.0.1',
    int     $port      = 4222,
    ?string $authToken = null,          // #[SensitiveParameter]
    string  $subject   = 'via.broadcast',
    bool    $tls       = false,
    ?string $tlsCaFile = null,
)
{% endverbatim %}{% endcode %}

    <h2 id="error-handling">Error observability</h2>
    <p>
        Both Redis and NATS brokers reconnect automatically with exponential backoff (1 s → 30 s cap).
        Register an error handler to receive a <code>\Throwable</code> on every connection drop:
    </p>
    {% code 'php' %}{% verbatim %}
$config->onBrokerError(function (\Throwable $e): void {
    // Safe summary only — do NOT log $e->getMessage() verbatim if it may
    // contain connection strings or credentials (OWASP: sensitive data exposure).
    error_log('[broker] connection lost: ' . get_class($e));
    $metrics->increment('broker.error');
});
{% endverbatim %}{% endcode %}
    <p>
        The handler fires for every reconnect attempt. When the broker is in the backoff window,
        <code>isConnected()</code> returns <code>false</code> and the <code>/_health</code> endpoint
        reports <code>"status":"degraded"</code>.
    </p>

    <h2 id="health-endpoint">Health endpoint</h2>
    <p>
        Every php-via server exposes <code>GET /_health</code> — no configuration needed, no devMode
        gate. Use it with your load balancer, Kubernetes liveness probes, or uptime monitors:
    </p>
    {% code 'bash' %}{% verbatim %}
curl https://myapp.example.com/_health
{% endverbatim %}{% endcode %}
    {% code 'json' %}{% verbatim %}
{
  "status": "ok",
  "version": "0.7.0",
  "broker": {
    "driver": "RedisBroker",
    "connected": true
  },
  "connections": {
    "contexts": 42,
    "sse": 38
  }
}
{% endverbatim %}{% endcode %}
    <p>
        HTTP <strong>200</strong> when the broker is connected. HTTP <strong>503</strong> when the
        broker is in the reconnect window (<code>"status":"degraded"</code>). The response contains
        no IP addresses, credentials, or per-user data.
    </p>
    <p>Example Caddy health check to remove a degraded node from rotation:</p>
    {% code 'caddy' %}{% verbatim %}
reverse_proxy node1:3000 node2:3000 {
    health_uri      /_health
    health_interval 5s
    health_timeout  2s
    health_status   200
}
{% endverbatim %}{% endcode %}

    <h2 id="connection-count">Connection count</h2>
    <p>
        Each php-via worker process opens its own connection(s) to the broker backend. With
        <code>RedisBroker</code> that is <strong>2 connections per worker</strong> (publish + subscribe).
        With <code>NatsBroker</code> it is <strong>1 connection per worker</strong>.
        Plan your Redis/NATS <code>maxclients</code> / connection limits accordingly.
    </p>
    <p>
        php-via defaults to a single worker (<code>worker_num: 1</code>). If you override this via
        <code>Config::withSwooleSettings(['worker_num' => N])</code>, multiply the above numbers by N.
    </p>

    <h2 id="next-steps">Next steps</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><a href="/docs/broadcasting">Broadcasting</a> — the broadcast() API and scope targets</li>
        <li><a href="/docs/scopes">Scopes</a> — which scopes cross node boundaries</li>
        <li><a href="/docs/deployment">Deployment</a> — systemd, Caddy, TLS setup</li>
    </ul>
</article>
{% endblock %}
